OE. been, beon, AS. beón to be, beóm I am; akin to OHG. bim, pim, G. bin, I am, Gael. & Ir. bu was, W. bod to be, Lith. bu-ti, O. Slav. by-ti, to be, L. fu-i I have been, fu-turus about to be, fo-re to be about to be, and perh. to fieri to become, Gr. fy^nai to be born, to be, Skr. bhū to be.  This verb is defective, and the parts lacking are supplied by verbs from other roots, is, was, which have no radical connection with be. The various forms, am, are, is, was, were, etc., are considered grammatically as parts of the verb “to be”, which, with its conjugational forms, is often called the substantive verb.  √97.  Cf. Future, Physic.

L.comparare, fr. compar like or equal to another; com- + par equal: cf. F. comparer. See Pair, Peer an equal, and cf. Compeer.
L. comparare to prepare, procure; com- + parare. See Prepare, Parade.
a.
F., fr. L. conditio (better condicio) agreement, compact, condition; con- + a root signifying to show, point out, akin to dicere to say, dicare to proclaim, dedicate. See Teach, Token.
Cf. LL. conditionare. See Condition, n.
L. connectere, -nexum; con- + nectere to bind. See Annex.
F. considérer, L. considerare, -sideratum, to consider, view attentively, prob. fr. con- + sidus, sideris, star, constellation; orig., therefore, to look at the stars. See Sidereal, and cf. Desire.
a.
L. consonans, -antis.
OE. contenen, conteinen, F. contenir, fr. L. continere, -tentum; con- + tenere to hold. See Tenable, and cf. Countenance.
a.
L. continens, prop., a holding together: cf. F. continent. See Continent, a.
F. continuer, L. continuare, -tinuatum, to connect, continue, fr. continuus. See Continuous, and cf. Continuate.
F. contrôle a counter register, contr. fr. contr-rôle; contre (L. contra) + rôle roll, catalogue. See Counter and Roll, and cf. Counterroll.
F. contrôler, fr. contrôle.
Of imitative origin.
Etymol. unknown.
AS. cōc, fr. L. cocus, coquus, coquus, fr. coquere to cook; akin to Gr. pe`ptein, Skr. pac, and to E. apricot, biscuit, concoct, dyspepsia, precocious. Cf. Pumpkin.
a.
F. copie, fr. L. copia abundance, number, LL. also, a transcript; co- + the root of opes riches. See Opulent, and cf. Copious.
Cf. F. copir, fr. LL. copiare. See Copy, n.
L.  cornu horn: cf. F. corne horn, hornlike excrescence. See Horn.
AS.  corn; akin to OS.  korn, D. koren, G., Dan., Sw., & Icel. korn, Goth. kaúrn, L.  granum, Russ. zerno. Cf.  Grain, Kernel.
OF. corniere, cornier, LL.  cornerium, corneria, fr. L.  cornu horn, end, point. See Horn.
a.
L. costa rib. See Coast.
OF. coster, couster, F.  coûter, fr. L. constare to stand at, to cost; con- + stare to stand. See Stand, and cf. Constant.
OF. cost, F. coût. See Cost, v. t.
F. coton, Sp. algodon the cotton plant and its wool, coton printed cotton, cloth, fr. Ar. qutun, alqutun, cotton wool. Cf. Acton, Hacqueton.
OF. coude. The l was inserted by mistake, under the influence of should and would.

OF. conter, and later (etymological spelling) compter, in modern French thus distinguished; conter to relate (cf. Recount, Account), compter to count; fr. L. computuare to reckon, compute; com- + putare to reckon, settle, order, prune, orig., to clean. See Pure, and cf. Compute.
F. conte and compte, with different meanings, fr. L. computus a computation, fr. computare. See Count, v. t.
F. conte, fr. L. comes, comitis, associate, companion, one of the imperial court or train, properly, one who goes with another; com- + ire to go, akin to Skr. i to go.
F. contrée, LL. contrata, fr. L.  contra over against, on the opposite side. Cf. Counter, adv., Contra.
a.
F. cours, course, L.  cursus, fr. currere to run. See Current.
OF.  covrir, F.  couvrir, fr. L.  cooperire; co-  +  operire to cover; probably fr.  ob towards, over + the root appearing in aperire to open. Cf. Aperient, Overt, Curfew.
Cf. F. couvert.
See Cowl a hood.
Cf. Icel.  kuga, Sw.  kufva to check, subdue, Dan.  kue.  Cf. Cuff, v. t.
Prob. from same root as cow, v. t.

Cf. LG. krus, G.  krause, crispness, krausen, kräusen, to crisp, curl, lay on folds; or perh. of Celtic origin; cf. Armor. kriz a wrinkle, crease, kriza to wrinkle, fold, W. crych a wrinkle, crychu to rumple, ripple, crease.
a.

OE.  crop, croppe, craw, top of a plant, harvest, AS.  crop, cropp, craw, top, bunch, ear of corn; akin to D. krop craw, G. kropf, Icel. kroppr hump or bunch on the body, body; but cf. also W. cropa, croppa, crop or craw of a bird, Ir. & Gael.  sgroban. Cf.  Croup, Crupper, Croup.
a.
OE.  crouden, cruden, AS. crūdan; cf. D.  kruijen to push in a wheelbarrow.
AS.  croda. See Crowd, v. t.
W. crwth; akin to Gael. cruit. Perh. named from its shape, and akin to Gr. kyrto`s curved, and E.  curve. Cf. Rote.
F. crier, cf. L.  quiritare to raise a plaintive cry, scream, shriek, perh. fr.  queri to complain; cf. Skr. cvas to pant, hiss, sigh. Cf. Quarrel a brawl, Querulous.
F.  cri, fr. crier to cry. See Cry, v. i.
a.

OE. cutten, kitten, ketten; prob. of Celtic origin; cf. W. cwtau to shorten, curtail, dock, cwta bobtailed, cwt tail, skirt, Gael.  cutaich to shorten, curtail, dock, cutach short, docked, cut a bobtail, piece, Ir. cut a short tail, cutach bobtailed. Cf. Coot.
a.
Prob. of Celtic origin; cf. Ir. daid, Gael. daidein, W. tad, OL. tata, Gr. ta`ta, te`tta, Skr. tāta.
F. danser, fr. OHG. dansōn to draw; akin to dinsan to draw, Goth. apinsan, and prob. from the same root (meaning to stretch) as E. thin. See Thin.
F. danse, of German origin. See Dance, v. i.

OE. danger, daunger, power, arrogance, refusal, difficulty, fr. OF. dagier, dongier (with same meaning), F. danger danger, fr. an assumed LL. dominiarium power, authority, from L. dominium power, property. See Dungeon, Domain, Dame.
a.
OE. day, dai, dei, AS. dæg; akin to OS., D., Dan., & Sw. dag, G. tag, Icel. dagr, Goth. dags; cf. Skr. dah (for dhagh ?) to burn. √69.  Cf. Dawn.
a.
Prob. from D. deel a plank, threshing floor. See Thill.
OE. delen, AS. d&aemacr_;lan, fr. d&aemacr_;l share; akin to OS. dēlian, D. deelen, G. theilen, teilen, Icel. deila, Sw. dela, Dan. dele, Goth. dailjan. See Deal, n.
a.
OE. deth, deað, AS. deáð; akin to OS. dōð, D. dood, G. tod, Icel. dauði, Sw. & Dan. död, Goth. dauþus; from a verb meaning to die. See Die, v. i., and cf. Dead.
L. decīdere; de- + caedere to cut, cut off; prob. akin to E. shed, v.: cf. F. décider.  Cf. Decision.
a.
a.
F. degré, OF. degret, fr. LL. degradare. See Degrade.
F. dépendre, fr. L. depend&unr_;re; de- + pend&unr_;re to hang. See Pendant.
L. describere, descriptum; de- + scribere to write: cf. OE. descriven, OF. descrivre, F. décrire. See Scribe, and cf. Descry.
OF. deserte, desserte, merit, recompense, fr. deservir, desservir, to merit. See Deserve.
F. désert, L. desertum, from desertus solitary, desert, pp. of deserere to desert; de- + serere to join together. See Series.
a.
Cf. L. desertus, p. p. of deserere to desert, F. déserter. See 2d Desert.

F. désigner to designate, cf. F. dessiner to draw, dessin drawing, dessein a plan or scheme; all, ultimately, from L. designare to designate; de- + signare to mark, mark out, signum mark, sign. See Sign, and cf. Design, n., Designate.
Cf. dessein, dessin.
F. déterminer, L. determinare, determinatum; de + terminare limit, terminus limit. See Term.

F. déveloper; dé- (L. dis-) + OF. voluper, voleper, to envelop, perh. from L. volup agreeably, delightfully, and hence orig., to make agreeable or comfortable by enveloping, to keep snug (cf. Voluptuous); or. perh. fr. a derivative of volvere, volutum, to roll (cf. Devolve).  Cf. Envelop.
Cf. F. dictionnaire. See Diction.

OE. deyen, dien, of Scand. origin; cf. Icel. deyja; akin to Dan. döe, Sw. dö, Goth. diwan (cf. Goth. afd&unr_;jan to harass), OFries. d&unr_;ia to kill, OS. doian to die, OHG. touwen, OSlav. daviti to choke, Lith. dovyti to torment.  Cf. Dead, Death.
OE. dee, die, F. dé, fr. L. datus given, thrown, p. p. of dare to give, throw. See Date a point of time.
L. differre; dif- = dis- + ferre to bear, carry: cf. F. différer. See 1st Bear, and cf. Defer, Delay.
a.
a.
L. discussus, p. p. of discutere to strike asunder (hence came the sense to separate mentally, distinguish); dis- + quatere to shake, strike. See Quash.
a.
L. dividere, divisum; di- = dis- + root signifying to part; cf. Skr. vyadh to pierce; perh. akin to L. vidua widow, and E. widow.  Cf. Device, Devise.
F. division, L. divisio, from dividere. See Divide.

AS. dōn; akin to D. doen, OS. duan, OHG. tuon, G. thun, Lith. deti, OSlav. dēti, OIr. dénim I do, Gr. tiqe`nai to put, Skr. dhā, and to E. suffix -dom, and prob. to L. facere to do, E. fact, and perh. to L. -dere in some compounds, as addere to add, credere to trust. √65. Cf. Deed, Deem, Doom, Fact, Creed, Theme.
Perh. a different word. OE. dugen, dowen, to avail, be of use, AS. dugan. See Doughty.
OF. doctur, L. doctor, teacher, fr. docere to teach. See Docile.
AS. docga; akin to D. dog mastiff, Dan. dogge, Sw. dogg.
D. daalder, LG. dahler, G. thaler, an abbreviation of Joachimsthaler, i. e., a piece of money first coined, about the year 1518, in the valley (G. thal) of St. Joachim, in Bohemia. See Dale.
a.

OE. dore, dure, AS. duru; akin to OS. dura, dor, D. deur, OHG. turi, door, tor gate, G. thür, thor, Icel. dyrr, Dan. dör, Sw. dörr, Goth. daur, Lith. durys, Russ. dvere, Olr. dorus, L. fores, Gr. &unr_;; cf. Skr. dur, dvāra. √246.  Cf. Foreign.
a.
OE. doblen, dublen, doublen, F. doubler, fr. L. duplare, fr. duplus. See Double, a.
Akin to LG. dune, dun, Icel. d&unr_;nn, Sw. dun, Dan. duun, G. daune, cf. D. dons; perh. akin to E. dust.
From the adverb.
For older adown, AS. adūn, adūne, prop., from or off the hill. See 3d Down, and cf. Adown, and cf. Adown.
From Down, adv.
a.

OE. dra&yogh_;en, drahen, draien, drawen, AS. dragan; akin to Icel. & Sw. draga, Dan. drage to draw, carry, and prob. to OS. dragan to bear, carry, D. dragen, G. tragen, Goth. dragan; cf. Skr. dhraj to move along, glide; and perh. akin to Skr. dhar to hold, bear. √73.  Cf. 2d Drag, Dray a cart, 1st Dredge.

Akin to OS. drōm, D. droom, G. traum, Icel. draumr, Dan. & Sw. dröm; cf. G. trügen to deceive, Skr. druh to harm, hurt, try to hurt. AS. dreám joy, gladness, and OS. drōm joy are, perh., different words; cf. Gr. qry^los noise.
Cf. AS. drēman, dr&ymacr_;man, to rejoice. See Dream, n.

OF. drecier to make straight, raise, set up, prepare, arrange, F. dresser, (assumed) LL. directiare, fr. L. dirigere, directum, to direct; dis- + regere to rule. See Right, and cf. Address, Adroit, Direct, Dirge.
AS. drincan; akin to OS. drinkan, D. drinken, G. trinken, Icel. drekka, Sw. dricka, Dan. drikke, Goth. drigkan.  Cf. Drench, Drunken, Drown.
AS. drīfan; akin to OS. drīban, D. drijven, OHG. trīban, G. treiben, Icel. drīfa, Goth. dreiban.  Cf. Drift, Drove.

OE. drope, AS. dropa; akin to OS. dropo, D. drop, OHG. tropo, G. tropfen, Icel. dropi, Sw. droppe; and Fr. AS. dreópan to drip, drop; akin to OS. driopan, D. druipen, OHG. triofan, G. triefen, Icel. drjūpa.  Cf. Drip, Droop.
OE. droppen, AS. dropan, v. i. See Drop, n.
a.
AS. drygan; cf. drugian to grow dry. See Dry, a.
Cf. Dan. dukke, Sw. docka, OHG. doccha, G. docke.  Cf. Doxy.
D. doek cloth, canvas, or Icel. dūkr cloth; akin to OHG. tuoh, G. tuch, Sw. duk, Dan. dug.
OE. duken, douken, to dive; akin to D. duiken, OHG. t&unr_;hhan, MHG. tucken, tücken, t&unr_;chen, G. tuchen.  Cf. 5th Duck.
OE. duke, doke. See Duck, v. t.
Orig., p. pr. of dure.
a.

AS. eáre; akin to OFries. áre, ár, OS. ōra, D. oor, OHG. ōra, G. ohr, Icel. eyra, Sw. öra, Dan. öre, Goth. auso, L. auris, Lith. ausis, Russ. ukho, Gr. o'y^s; cf. L. audire to hear, Gr. 'ai`ein, Skr. av to favor , protect.  Cf. Auricle, Orillon.
AS. ear; akin to D. aar, OHG. ahir, G. ähre, Icel., Sw., & Dan. ax, Goth. ahs. √1.  Cf. Awn, Edge.
OE. erien, AS. erian; akin to OFries. era, OHG. erran, MHG. eren, ern, Prov. G. aren, ären, Icel. erja, Goth. arjan, Lith. arti, OSlav. orati, L. arare, Gr. &unr_;.  Cf. Arable.
OE. erli, erliche, AS. &aemacr_;rlīce; &aemacr_;r sooner + līc like. See Ere, and Like.
a.
AS. eorðe; akin to OS. ertha, OFries. irthe, D. aarde, OHG. erda, G. erde, Icel. jörð, Sw. & Dan. jord, Goth. aīrþa, OHG. ero, Gr. &unr_;, adv., to earth, and perh. to E. ear to plow.
From Ear to plow.
OE. ese, eise, F. aise; akin to Pr. ais, aise, OIt. asio, It. agio; of uncertain origin; cf. L. ansa handle, occasion, opportunity.  Cf. Agio, Disease.
OE. esen, eisen, OF. aisier. See Ease, n.

OE. est, east, AS. eást; akin to D. oost, oosten, OHG. ōstan, G. ost, osten, Icel. austr, Sw. ost, Dan. öst, östen, Lith. auszra dawn, L. aurora (for ausosa), Gr. 'hw`s, "e`os, 'a`yws, Skr. ushas; cf. Skr. ush to burn, L. urere. √149, 288.  Cf. Aurora, Easter, Sterling.
a.

OE. eten, AS. etan; akin to OS. etan, OFries. eta, D. eten, OHG. ezzan, G. essen, Icel. eta, Sw. äta, Dan. æde, Goth. itan, Ir. & Gael. ith, W. ysu, L. edere, Gr. 'e`dein, Skr. ad. √6.  Cf. Etch, Fret to rub, Edible.
OE. eg, egge, AS. ecg; akin to OHG. ekka, G. ecke, Icel. & Sw. egg, Dan. eg, and to L. acies, Gr. 'akh` point, Skr. açri edge. √1.  Cf. Egg, v. t., Eager, Ear spike of corn, Acute.
L. effectus, fr. efficere, effectum, to effect; ex + facere to make: cf. F. effet, formerly also spelled effect. See Fact.
OE., fr. Icel. egg; akin to AS. æg (whence OE. ey), Sw. ägg, Dan. æg, G. & D. ei, and prob. to OSlav. aje, jaje, L. ovum, Gr. 'w,o`n, Ir. ugh, Gael. ubh, and perh. to L. avis bird.  Cf. Oval.
OE. eggen, Icel. eggja, fr. egg edge. &unr_;&unr_;. See Edge.
See Ait.
a.
a.
F. élément, L. elementum.
a.
OE. &  AS. ende; akin to OS. endi, D. einde, eind, OHG. enti, G. ende, Icel. endir, endi, Sw. ände, Dan. ende, Goth. andeis, Skr. anta. √208.  Cf. Ante-, Anti-, Answer.
OF. enemi, F. ennemi, from L. inimicus; in- (negative) + amicus friend. See Amicable.
a.
F. énergie, LL. energia, fr. Gr.&unr_;, fr. &unr_; active; &unr_; in + &unr_; work. See In, and Work.
F. engin skill, machine, engine, L. ingenium natural capacity, invention; in in + the root of gignere to produce. See Genius, and cf. Ingenious, Gin a snare.
a.
OE. entren, enteren, F. entrer, fr. L. intrare, fr. intro inward, contr. fr. intero (sc. loco), fr. inter in between, between. See Inter-, In, and cf. Interior.
a.
L. aequatus, p. p. of aequare to make level or equal, fr. aequus level, equal. See Equal.
OE. eve, even, efen, æfen. AS. &aemacr_;fen; akin to OS. āband, OFries, āvend, D. avond, OHG. āband, Icel. aptan, Sw. afton, Dan. aften; of unknown origin.  Cf. Eve, Evening.
a.
AS. efne. See Even, a., and cf. E'en.
AS. &aemacr_;fnung. See even, n., and cf. Eve.
L. eventus, fr. evenire to happen, come out; e out + venire to come. See Come.
F. éventer to fan, divulge, LL. eventare to fan, fr., L. e out + ventus wind.
OE. ever, æfre, AS. æfre; perh. akin to AS. ā always.  Cf. Aye, Age,Evry, Never.
a.
a.
From L. exactus, p. p. of exigere; or fr. LL. exactare: cf. OF. exacter. See Exact, a.
A later form for ensample, fr. L. exemplum, orig., what is taken out of a larger quantity, as a sample, from eximere to take out. See Exempt, and cf. Ensample, Sample.
L. exceptus, p. p. of excipere to take or draw out, to except; ex out + capere to take: cf. F. excepter. See Capable.
Originally past participle, or verb in the imperative mode.
L. excitare; ex out + citare to move rapidly, to rouse: cf. OF. esciter, exciter, F. exciter. See Cite.
F. exercice, L. exercitium, from exercere, exercitum, to drive on, keep, busy, prob. orig., to thrust or drive out of the inclosure; ex out + arcere to shut up, inclose. See Ark.
L. expectatum, to look out for, await, expect; ex + out spectare to look at. See Spectacle.
F. expérience, L. experientia, tr. experiens, experientis, p. pr. of experiri, expertus, to try; ex out + the root of peritus experienced. See Peril, and cf. Expert.
L. experimentum, fr. experiri to try: cf. OF. esperiment, experiment. See Experience.
Prob. fr. nye, an eye being for a nye. See Nye.

OE. eghe, eighe, eie, eye, AS.  eáge; akin to OFries. āge, OS. ōga, D. oog, Ohg. ouga, G. auge, Icel. auga, Sw. öga, Dan. öie, Goth. augō; cf. OSlav. oko, Lith. akis, L. okulus, Gr. 'o`kkos, eye, 'o`sse, the two eyes, Skr. akshi. √10, 212.  Cf. Diasy, Ocular, Optic, Eyelet, Ogle.
F., from L. facies form, shape, face, perh. from facere to make (see Fact); or perh. orig. meaning appearance, and from a root meaning to shine, and akin to E. fancy.  Cf. Facetious.
L. factum, fr. facere to make or do.  Cf. Feat, Affair, Benefit, Defect, Fashion, and -fy.
a.
OE. feire, OF. feire, F. foire, fr. L. fariae, pl., days of rest, holidays, festivals, akin to festus festal. See Feast.

AS. feallan; akin to D. vallen, OS. & OHG. fallan, G. fallen, Icel. Falla, Sw. falla, Dan. falde, Lith. pulti, L. fallere to deceive, Gr. sfa`llein to cause to fall, Skr. sphal, sphul, to tremble.  Cf. Fail, Fell, v. t., to cause to fall.
L. familia, fr. famulus servant; akin to Oscan famel servant, cf. faamat he dwells, Skr. dhāman house, fr. dhāto set, make, do: cf. F. famille.  Cf. Do, v. t., Doom, Fact, Feat.
a.
See Farrow.
a.
OE. ferme rent, lease, F. ferme, LL. firma, fr. L. firmus firm, fast, firmare to make firm or fast.  See Firm, a. & n.
AS. fæstan; akin to D. vasten, OHG. fastēn, G. fasten, Icel. & Sw. fasta, Dan. faste, Goth. fastan to keep, observe, fast, and prob. to E. fast firm.
OE. faste, fast; cf. AS. fæsten, OHG. fasta, G. faste. See Fast, v. i.
a.
OE. faste firmly, strongly, quickly, AS. fæste.  See Fast, a.
See Vat, n.
a.
OE. fatten, AS. f&aemacr_;ttian. See Fat, a., and cf. Fatten.

OE. fader, AS. fæder; akin to OS. fadar, D. vader, OHG. fatar, G. vater, Icel. faðir Sw. & Dan. fader, OIr. athir, L. pater, Gr. path`r, Skr. pitr, perh. fr. Skr. pā protect. √75, 247.  Cf. Papa, Paternal, Patriot, Potential, Pablum.
Written also favour.
Written also favour.
OE. fer, feer, fere, AS. f&aemacr_;r a coming suddenly upon, fear, danger; akin to D. vaar, OHG. fāra danger, G. gefahr, Icel. fār harm, mischief, plague, and to E. fare, peril. See Fare.
OE. feren, faeren, to frighten, to be afraid, AS. f&aemacr_;ran to terrify.  See Fear, n.
AS. fēdan, fr. fōda food; akin to OS. fōdian, OFries. fēda, fōda, D. voeden, OHG. fuottan, Icel. fæða, Sw. föda, Dan. föde. √75.  See Food.
AS. fēlan; akin to OS. gifōlian to perceive, D. voelen to feel, OHG. fuolen, G. fühlen, Icel. fālma to grope, and prob. to AS. folm palm of the hand, L. palma.  Cf. Fumble, Palm.
See Feat, n.
a.
Cf. L. fel gall, bile, or E. fell, a.
AS. fell; akin to D. vel, OHG. fel, G. fell, Icel. fell (in comp.), Goth fill in þrutsfill leprosy, L. pellis skin, Gr. pe`lla.  Cf. Film, Peel, Pell, n.
Icel. fell, fjally; akin to Sw. fjäll a ridge or chain of mountains, Dan. fjeld mountain, rock and prob. to G. fels rock, or perh. to feld field, E. field.
AS. fellan, a causative verb fr. feallan to fall; akin to D. vellen, G. fällen, Icel. fella, Sw. fälla, Dan. fælde. See Fall, v. i.
Cf. Gael. fill to fold, plait, Sw. fåll a hem.
AS. felt; akin to D. vilt, G. filz, and possibly to Gr. &unr_; hair or wool wrought into felt, L. pilus hair, pileus a felt cap or hat.
a.
OE. feld, fild, AS. feld; akin to D. veld, G. feld, Sw. fält, Dan. felt, Icel. fold field of grass, AS. folde earth, land, ground, OS. folda.
F. figue the fruit of the tree, Pr. figa, fr. L. ficus fig tree, fig.  Cf. Fico.
See Fico, Fig, n.
OE. fihten, fehten, AS. feohtan; akin to D. vechten, OHG. fehtan, G. fechten, Sw. fäkta, Dan. fegte, and perh. to E. fist; cf. L. pugnare to fight, pugnus fist.
OE. fight, feht, AS. feoht. See Fight, v. i.
F., figure, L. figura; akin to fingere to form, shape, feign. See Feign.
F. figurer, L. figurare, fr. figura. See Figure, n.
See Thill.
OE. fillen, fullen, AS. fyllan, fr. full full; akin to D. vullen, G. füllen, Icel. fylla, Sw. fylla, Dan. fylde, Goth. fulljan. See Full, a.
AS. fyllo. See Fill, v. t.
a.
AS. findan; akin to D. vinden, OS. & OHG. findan, G. finden, Dan. finde, icel. & Sw. finna, Goth. finþan; and perh. to L. petere to seek, Gr. pi`ptein to fall, Skr. pat to fall, fly, E. petition.
a.
From Fine, a.

OE. fin, L. finis end, also in LL., a final agreement or concord between the lord and his vassal; a sum of money paid at the end, so as to make an end of a transaction, suit, or prosecution; mulct; penalty; cf. OF. fin end, settlement, F. fin end. See Finish, and cf. Finance.
From Fine, n.
OF. finer, F. finir. See Finish, v. t.
AS. finger; akin to D. vinger, OS. & OHG. fingar, G. finger, Icel. fingr, Sw. & Dan. finger, Goth. figgrs; of unknown origin; perh. akin to E. fang.

F. finir (with a stem finiss- in several forms, whence E. -ish: see -ish.),fr. L. finire to limit, finish, end, fr. finis boundary, limit, end; perh. for fidnis, and akin findere to cleave, E. fissure.
OE. fir, fyr, fur AS. f&ymacr_;r; akin to D. vuur, OS. & OHG. fiur, G. feuer, Icel. f&ymacr_;ri, fūrr, Gr. py^r, and perh. to L. purus pure, E. pure Cf. Empyrean, Pyre.

OE. fisch, fisc, fis, AS. fisc; akin to D. visch, OS. & OHG. fisk, G. fisch, Icel. fiskr, Sw. & Dan. fisk, Goth. fisks, L. piscis, Ir. iasg.  Cf. Piscatorial. In some cases, such as fish joint, fish plate, this word has prob. been confused with fish, fr. F. fichea peg.
OE. fischen, fisken, fissen, AS. fiscian; akin to G. fischen, OHG. fisc&unr_;n, Goth. fisk&unr_;n. See Fish the animal.
AS. fitt a song.

AS. fit strife, fight; of uncertain origin. √ 77.

AS. flōr; akin to D. vloer, G. flur field, floor, entrance hall, Icel. flōr floor of a cow stall, cf. Ir. & Gael. lar floor, ground, earth, W. llawr, perh. akin to L. planus level.  Cf. Plain smooth.
AS. flōwan; akin to D. vloeijen, OHG. flawen to wash, Icel. flōa to deluge, Gr. plw`ein to float, sail, and prob. ultimately to E. float, fleet. √80.  Cf. Flood.
OE. flour, OF. flour, flur, flor, F. fleur, fr. L. flos, floris.  Cf. Blossom, Effloresce, Floret, Florid, Florin, Flour, Flourish.
From the noun.  Cf. Flourish.

OE. fleen, fleen, fleyen, flegen, AS. fleógan; akin to D. vliegen, OHG. fliogan, G. fliegen, Icel. fljūga, Sw. flyga, Dan. flyve, Goth. us-flaugjan to cause to fly away, blow about, and perh. to L. pluma feather, E. plume. √84.  Cf. Fledge, Flight, Flock of animals.
OE. flie, flege, AS. fl&ymacr_;ge, fleóge, fr. fleógan to fly; akin to D. vlieg, OHG. flioga, G. fliege, Icel. & Sw. fluga, Dan. flue. √ 84.  See Fly, v. i.
a.
OE. foluwen, folwen, folgen, AS. folgian, fylgean, fylgan; akin to D. volgen, OHG. folgēn, G. folgen, Icel. fylgja, Sw. följa, Dan. fölge, and perh. to E. folk.

OE. fode, AS. fōda; akin to Icel. fæða, fæði, Sw. föda, Dan. & LG. föde, OHG. fatunga, Gr. patei^sthai to eat, and perh. to Skr. pā to protect, L. pascere to feed, pasture, pabulum food, E. pasture. √75.  Cf. Feed, Fodder food, Foster to cherish.

OE. fot, foot, pl. fet, feet. AS. fōt, pl. fēt; akin to D. voet, OHG. fuoz, G. fuss, Icel. fōtr, Sw. fot, Dan. fod, Goth. fōtus, L. pes, Gr. poy`s, Skr. pād, Icel. fet step, pace measure of a foot, feta to step, find one's way. √77, 250.  Cf. Antipodes, Cap-a-pie, Expedient, Fet to fetch, Fetlock, Fetter, Pawn a piece in chess, Pedal.

AS. for, fore; akin to OS. for, fora, furi, D. voor, OHG. fora, G. vor, OHG. furi, G. für, Icel. fyrir, Sw. för, Dan. for, adv. för, Goth. faúr, faúra, L. pro, Gr. &unr_;, Skr. pra-. √ 202.  Cf. Fore, First, Foremost, Forth, Pro-.

OF. forcier, F. forcer, fr. LL. forciare, fortiare. See Force, n.
OF. forest, F. forêt, LL. forestis, also, forestus, forestum, foresta, prop., open ground reserved for the chase, fr. L. foris, foras, out of doors, abroad. See Foreign.
a.
OE. & F. forme, fr. L. forma; cf. Skr. dhariman.  Cf. Firm.
F. former, L. formare, fr. forma. See Form, n.
OE., fr. AS. foreweard; fore before + weard a ward. See Ward, n.
a.
F. fondre, L. fundere to found, pour.
F. fonder, L. fundare, fr. fundus bottom. See 1st Bottom, and cf. Founder, v. i., Fund.
a.
F. fraction, L. fractio a breaking, fr. frangere, fractum, to break. See Break.
a.
OE. freen, freoien, AS. freógan. See Free, a.
a.

OE. frend, freond, AS. freónd, prop. p. pr. of freón, freógan, to love; akin to D. vriend friend, OS. friund friend, friohan to love, OHG. friunt friend, G. freund, Icel. frændi kinsman, Sw. frände. Goth. frijōnds friend, frijōn to love. √83. See Free, and cf. Fiend.
AS. fram, from; akin to OS. fram out, OHG. & Icel. fram forward, Sw. fram, Dan. frem, Goth. fram from, prob. akin to E. forth. &unr_;202.  Cf. Fro, Foremost.
F. frant forehead, L. frons, frontis; perh. akin to E. brow.

OE. fruit, frut, F. fruit, from L. fructus enjoyment, product, fruit, from frui, p. p. fructus, to enjoy; akin to E. brook, v. t. See Brook, v. t., and cf. Fructify, Frugal.
a.

OE. fullen, OF. fuler, fouler, F. fouler, LL. fullare, fr. L. fullo fuller, cloth fuller, cf. Gr. &unr_; shining, white, AS. fullian to whiten as a fuller, to baptize, fullere a fuller.  Cf. Defile to foul, Foil to frustrate, Fuller. n.
Perh. of Celtic origin; cf. Ir. & Gael. fonn pleasure.
a.
OE. game, gamen, AS. gamen, gomen, play, sport; akin to OS., OHG., & Icel. gaman, Dan. gammen mirth, merriment, OSw. gamman joy.  Cf. Gammon a game, Backgammon, Gamble v. i.
a.
OE. gamen, game&unr_;en, to rejoice, AS. gamenian to play. See Game, n.
OE. gardin, OF. gardin, jardin, F. jardin, of German origin; cf. OHG. garto, G. garten; akin to AS. geard. See Yard an inclosure.

OE. geten, AS. gitan, gietan (in comp.); akin to Icel. geta, Goth. bigitan to find, L. prehendere to seize, take, Gr. chanda`nein to hold, contain.  Cf. Comprehend, Enterprise, Forget, Impregnable, Prehensile.
OE. given, yiven, yeven, AS. gifan, giefan; akin to D. geven, OS. geðan, OHG. geban, G. geben, Icel. gefa, Sw. gifva, Dan. give, Goth. giban.  Cf. Gift, n.
AS. gladian. See Glad, a., and cf. Gladden, v. t.

OE. gan, gon, AS. gān, akin to D. gaan, G. gehn, gehen, OHG. gēn, gān, SW. gå, Dan. gaae; cf. Gr. kicha`nai to reach, overtake, Skr. hā to go, AS. gangan, and E. gang. The past tense in AS., eode, is from the root i to go, as is also Goth. iddja went. √47a.  Cf. Gang, v. i., Wend.
OF. governer, F. gouverner, fr. L. gubernare to steer, pilot, govern, Gr. kyberna^n.  Cf. Gubernatorial.
a.
OE. gras, gres, gers, AS, græs, gærs; akin to OFries. gres, gers, OS., D., G., Icel., &  Goth. gras, Dan. græs, Sw. gräs, and prob. to E. green, grow.  Cf. Graze.
a.
named after Louis Harold Gray, English radiobiologist.
a.

OE. ground, grund, AS. grund; akin to D. grond, OS., G., Sw., & Dan. grund, Icel. grunnr bottom, Goth. grundus (in composition); perh. orig. meaning, dust, gravel, and if so perh. akin to E. grind.
F groupe, It. gruppo, groppo, cluster, bunch, packet, group; of G. origin: cf. G. kropf craw, crop, tumor, bunch. See Crop, n.
Cf. F. grouper. See Group, n.
AS. grōwan; akin to D. groeijen, Icel. grōa, Dan. groe, Sw. gro.  Cf. Green, Grass.
OE. gessen; akin to Dan. gisse, Sw. gissa, Icel. gizha, D. gissen: cf. Dan. giette to guess, Icel. geta to get, to guess. Probably originally, to try to get, and akin to E. get. See Get.
OE. giae, F. guide, It. guida. See Guide, v. t.

OE. gonne, gunne; of uncertain origin; cf. Ir., Gael., & LL. gunna, W. gum; possibly (like cannon) fr. L. canna reed, tube; or abbreviated fr. OF. mangonnel, E. mangonel, a machine for hurling stones.

AS. healf. See Half, a.
AS. hand, hond; akin to D., G., & Sw. hand, OHG. hant, Dan. haand, Icel. hönd, Goth. handus, and perh. to Goth. hinþan to seize (in comp.).  Cf. Hunt.
OE. happenen, hapnen. See Hap to happen.

OE. harde, AS. hearde.

AS. hæt, hætt; akin to Dan. hat, Sw. hatt, Icel. hattr a hat, höttr hood, D. hoed hat, G. hut, OHG. huot, and prob. to L. cassis helmet.  √13.  Cf. Hood.

OE. haven, habben, AS. habben (imperf. hæfde, p. p. gehæfd); akin to OS. hebbian, D. hebben, OFries. hebba, OHG. habēn, G. haben, Icel. hafa, Sw. hafva, Dan. have, Goth. haban, and prob. to L. habere, whence F. avoir.  Cf. Able, Avoirdupois, Binnacle, Habit.

AS. hē, masc., heó, fem., hit, neut.; pl. hī, or hie, hig; akin to OFries. hi, D. hij, OS. he, hi, G. heute to-day, Goth. himma, dat. masc., this, hina, accus. masc., and hita, accus. neut., and prob. to L. his this.  √183.  Cf. It.

OE. hed, heved, heaved, AS. heáfod; akin to D. hoofd, OHG. houbit, G. haupt, Icel. höfuð, Sw. hufvud, Dan. hoved, Goth. haubiþ.  The word does not correspond regularly to L. caput head (cf. E. Chief, Cadet, Capital), and its origin is unknown.
a.

OE. heren, AS,. hiéran, h&ymacr_;ran, hēran; akin to OS. hōrian, OFries. hera, hora, D. hooren, OHG. hōren, G. hören, Icel. heyra, Sw. höra, Dan. hore, Goth. hausjan, and perh. to Gr. 'akoy`ein, E. acoustic.  Cf. Hark, Hearken.

OE. harte, herte, heorte, AS. heorte; akin to OS. herta, OFies. hirte, D. hart, OHG. herza, G. herz, Icel. hjarta, Sw. hjerta, Goth. haírtō, Lith. szirdis, Russ. serdtse, Ir. cridhe, L. cor, Gr. kardi`a, kh^r.  √277.  Cf. Accord, Discord, Cordial, 4th Core, Courage.
OE. hete, hæte, AS. h&aemacr_;tu, h&aemacr_;to, fr. hāt hot; akin to OHG. heizi heat, Dan. hede, Sw. hetta. See Hot.

OE. hire, here, hir, hure, gen. and dat. sing., AS. hire, gen. and dat. sing. of héo she. from the same root as E. he. See He.
OE. here, hire, AS. heora, hyra, gen. pl. of hē. See He.
OE. her, AS. hēr; akin to OS. hēr, D. hier, OHG. hiar, G. hier, Icel. & Goth. hēr, Dan. her, Sw. här; fr. root of E. he. See He.

OE. hil, hul, AS. hyll; akin to OD. hille, hil, L. collis, and prob. to E. haulm, holm, and column.  Cf. 2d Holm.
AS. him, dat. of hē. √183.  See He.
AS. his of him, his, gen. masc. & neut. of hē, neut. hit. See He.
OE. hitten, hutten, of Scand. origin; cf. Dan. hitte to hit, find, Sw. & Icel. hitta.
D. hol hole, hollow. See Hole.

OE. hol, hole, AS. hol, hole, cavern, from hol, a., hollow; akin to D. hol, OHG. hol, G. hohl, Dan. huul hollow, hul hole, Sw. hål, Icel. hola; prob. from the root of AS. helan to conceal. See Hele, Hell, and cf. Hold of a ship.
AS. holian. See Hole, n.

OE. hom, ham, AS. hām; akin to OS. hēm, D. & G. heim, Sw. hem, Dan. hiem, Icel. heimr abode, world, heima home, Goth. haims village, Lith. këmas, and perh. to Gr. kw`mh village, or to E. hind a peasant; cf. Skr. kshēma abode, place of rest, security, kshi to dwell. √20, 220.

Cf. Icel. hōp a small bay or inlet.

AS. hopian; akin to D. hopen, Sw. hoppan, Dan. haabe, G. hoffen. See 2nd Hope.

AS. horsion.

OE. hour, our, hore, ure, OF. hore, ore, ure, F. heure, L. hora, fr. Gr. &unr_;, orig., a definite space of time, fixed by natural laws; hence, a season, the time of the day, an hour. See Year, and cf. Horologe, Horoscope.

OE. hous, hus, AS. h&unr_;s; akin to OS. & OFries. h&unr_;s, D. huis, OHG. h&unr_;s, G. haus, Icel. h&unr_;s, Sw. hus, Dan. huus, Goth. gudh&unr_;s, house of God, temple; and prob. to E. hide to conceal. See Hide, and cf. Hoard, Husband, Hussy, Husting.
AS. h&unr_;sian.
OE. how, hou, hu, hwu, AS. h&unr_;, from the same root as hwā, hwæt, who, what, pron. interrog.; akin to OS. hwōw, D. hoe, cf. G. wie how, Goth. hwē wherewith, hwaiwa how. √182. See Who, and cf. Why.

OE. hundred, AS. hundred a territorial division; hund hundred + a word akin to Goth. ga-raþjan to count, L. ratio reckoning, account; akin to OS. hunderod, hund, D. hondred, G. hundert, OHG. also hunt, Icel. hundrað, Dan. hundrede, Sw. hundra, hundrade, Goth. hund, Lith. szimtas, Russ. sto, W. cant, Ir. cead, L. centum, Gr. "ekato`s, Skr. çata. √309.  Cf. Cent, Century, Hecatomb, Quintal, and Reason.

AS. huntian to hunt; cf. hentan to follow, pursue, Goth. hin&unr_;an (in comp.) to seize. √36.  Cf. Hent.
OE. horien; cf. OSw. hurra to whirl round, dial. Sw. hurr great haste, Dan. hurre to buzz, Icel. hurr hurly-burly, MHG. hurren to hurry, and E. hurr, whir to hurry; all prob. of imitative origin.
OE. i, ich, ic, AS. ic; akin to OS. & D. ik, OHG. ih, G. ich, Icel. ek, Dan. jeg, Sw. jag, Goth. ik, OSlav. az', Russ. ia, W. i, L. ego, Gr. 'egw`, 'egw`n, Skr. aham. √179.  Cf. Egoism.
OE. is, iis, AS. īs; aksin to D. ijs, G. eis, OHG. īs, Icel. īss, Sw. is, Dan. iis, and perh. to E. iron.
L. idea, Gr. &unr_;, fr. &unr_; to see; akin to E. wit: cf. F. idée. See Wit.

OE. if, gif, AS. gif; akin to OFries. ief, gef, ef, OS. ef, of, D. of, or, whether, if, G. ob whether, if, OHG. oba, ibu, Icel. ef, Goth. iba, ibai, an interrogative particle; properly a case form of a noun meaning, doubt (cf. OHG. iba doubt, condition, Icel. if, ef, ifi, efi), and therefore orig. meaning, on condition that.
F. imaginer, L. imaginari, p. p. imaginatus, fr. imago image. See Image.

AS. is; akin to G. & Goth. ist, L. est, Gr. &unr_;, Skr. asti. √9.  Cf. Am, Entity, Essence, Absent.
OE. it, hit, AS. hit; cf. D. het. √181. See He.
OF. joir, F. jouir. See Joy, n.
Cf. F. jupe a long petticoat, a skirt.  Cf. juppon.

OE. killen, kellen, cullen, to kill, strike; perh. the same word as cwellen, quellen, to kill (cf. Quell), or perh. rather akin to Icel. kolla to hit in the head, harm, kollr top, summit, head, Sw. kulle, D. kollen to kill with the ax.

OE. kinde, cunde, AS. cynd. See Kind, a.

AS. cyng, cyning; akin to OS. kuning, D. koning, OHG. kuning, G. könig, Icel. konungr, Sw. konung, Dan. konge; formed with a patronymic ending, and fr. the root of E. kin; cf. Icel. konr a man of noble birth. √44. See Kin.

OE. knowen, knawen, AS. cnäwan; akin to OHG. chnäan (in comp.), Icel. knä to be able, Russ. znate to know, L. gnoscere, noscere, Gr. gighw`skein, Skr. jnā; fr. the root of E. can, v. i., ken. √45.  See Ken, Can to be able, and cf. Acquaint, Cognition, Gnome, Ignore, Noble, Note.

AS. lac, L. lacus; akin to AS. lagu lake, sea, Icel. lögr; OIr. loch; cf. Gr. la`kkos pond, tank.  Cf. Loch, Lough.
AS. land, lond; akin to D., G., Icel., Sw., Dan., and Goth. land.

Cf. La.

OF. lei faith, law, F. loi law. See Legal.

OE. leggen, AS. lecgan, causative, fr. licgan to lie; akin to D. leggen, G. legen, Icel. leggja, Goth. lagjan. See Lie to be prostrate.
OE. led, leed, lead, AS. leád; akin to D. lood, MHG. lōt, G. loth plummet, sounding lead, small weight, Sw. & Dan. lod. √123.

OE. leden, AS. l&aemacr_;dan (akin to OS. lēdian, D. leiden, G. leiten, Icel. leīða, Sw. leda, Dan. lede), properly a causative fr. AS. liðan to go; akin to OHG. līdan, Icel. līða, Goth. leiþan (in comp.).  Cf. Lode, Loath.

OE. lernen, leornen, AS. leornian; akin to OS. linōn, for lirnōn, OHG. lirnēn, lernēn, G. lernen, fr. the root of AS. l&aemacr_;ran to teach, OS. lērian, OHG. lēran, G. lehren, Goth. laisjan, also Goth lais I know, leis acquainted (in comp.); all prob. from a root meaning, to go, go over, and hence, to learn; cf. AS. leoran to go.  Cf. Last a mold of the foot, lore.

See Levy.
OE. leve, leave, AS. leáf; akin to leóf pleasing, dear, E. lief, D. oorlof leave, G. arlaub, and erlauben to permit, Icel. leyfi.  √124.  See Lief.
OE. leven, AS. l&unr_;fan, fr. lāf remnant, heritage; akin to lifian, libban, to live, orig., to remain; cf. belīfan to remain, G. bleiben, Goth. bileiban. √119.  See Live, v.
a.
Icel. leggr; akin to Dan. læg calf of the leg, Sw. lägg.
OE. lengthe, AS. lengð, fr. lang, long, long; akin to D. lengte, Dan. længde, Sw. längd, Icel. lengd. See Long, a.

AS. l&aemacr_;s. See Less, adj., and cf. Lest.
OE. letten, AS. lettan to delay, to hinder, fr. læt slow; akin to D. letten to hinder, G. verletzen to hurt, Icel. letja to hold back, Goth. latjan. See Late.

OE. leten, læten (past tense lat, let, p. p. laten, leten, lete), AS. l&aemacr_;tan (past tense lēt, p. p. l&aemacr_;ten); akin to OFries. lēta, OS. lātan, D. laten, G. lassen, OHG. lāzzan, Icel. lāta, Sw. låta, Dan. lade, Goth. lētan, and L. lassus weary. The original meaning seems to have been, to let loose, let go, let drop. Cf. Alas, Late, Lassitude, Let to hinder.

OE. lettre, F. lettre, OF. letre, fr. L. littera, litera, a letter; pl., an epistle, a writing, literature, fr. linere, litum, to besmear, to spread or rub over; because one of the earliest modes of writing was by graving the characters upon tablets smeared over or covered with wax. Pliny, xiii. 11. See Liniment, and cf. Literal.
OE. level, livel, OF. livel, F. niveau, fr. L. libella level, water level, a plumb level, dim. of libra pound, measure for liquids, balance, water poise, level. Cf. Librate, Libella.

AS. rest, ræst, rest; akin to D. rust, G. rast. OHG. rasta, Dan. & Sw. rast rest, repose, Icel. röst the distance between two resting places, a mole, Goth. rasta a mile, also to Goth. razn house, Icel. rann, and perhaps to G. ruhe rest, repose, AS. rōw, Gr. 'erwh`.  Cf. Ransack.

OF. roeler, roler, F. rouler, LL. rotulare, fr. L. royulus, rotula, a little wheel, dim. of rota wheel; akin to G. rad, and to Skr. ratha car, chariot.  Cf. Control, Roll, n., Rotary.

OE. roum, rum, space, AS. rūm; akin to OS., OFries. & Icel. rūm, D. ruim, G. raum, OHG. rūm, Sw. & Dan. rum, Goth. rūms, and to AS. rūm, adj., spacious, D. ruim, Icel. rūmr, Goth. rūms; and prob. to L. rus country (cf. Rural), Zend rava&ndot_;h wide, free, open, ravan a plain.

OE. ship, schip, AS. scip; akin to OFries. skip, OS. scip, D. schip, G. schiff, OHG. scif, Dan. skib, Sw. skeep, Icel. & Goth. skip; of unknown origin.  Cf. Equip, Skiff, Skipper.
OE. sho, scho, AS. scōh, sceóh; akin to OFries. skō, OS. skōh, D. schoe, schoen, G. schuh, OHG. scuoh, Icel. skōr, Dan. & Sw. sko, Goth. skōhs; of unknown origin.
AS. sc&unr_;ian, sce&unr_;ian. See Shoe, n.
OE. shoppe, schoppe, AS. sceoppa a treasury, a storehouse, stall, booth; akin to scypen a shed, LG. schup a shed, G. schoppen, schuppen, a shed, a coachhouse, OHG. scopf.
OE. schore; akin to LG. schore, D. schoor, OD. schoore, Icel. skor&unr_;a, and perhaps to E. shear, as being a piece cut off.
OE. schoren. See Shore a prop.
OE. schore, AS. score, probably fr. scieran, and so meaning properly, that which is shorn off, edge; akin to OD. schoore, schoor. See Shear, v. t.
a.
AS. sceortian.
OE. sholde, shulde, scholde, schulde, AS. scolde, sceolde. See Shall.
OE. shulder, shuldre, schutder, AS. sculdor; akin to D. schoulder, G. schulter, OHG. scultarra, Dan. skulder, Sw. skuldra.
OE. shouten, of unknown origin; perhaps akin to shoot; cf. Icel. skūta, skūti, a taunt.

OE. schowen, shewen, schewen, shawen, AS. sceáwian, to look, see, view; akin to OS. scaw&unr_;n, OFries. skawia, D. schouwen, OHG. scouw&unr_;n, G. schauen, Dan. skue, Sw. sk&unr_;da, Icel. sko&unr_;a, Goth. usskawjan to waken, skuggwa a mirror, Icel. skuggy shade, shadow, L. cavere to be on one's guard, Gr. &unr_;&unr_;&unr_; to mark, perceive, hear, Skr. kavi wise.  Cf. Caution, Scavenger, Sheen.
Written also shew.
Formerly written also shew.
AS. sīde; akin to D. zijde, G. seite, OHG. sīta, Icel. sī&unr_;a, Dan. side, Sw. sida; cf. AS. sīd large, spacious, Icel. sī&unr_;r long, hanging.
AS. sīd. Cf Side, n.
OE. sight, siþt, siht, AS. siht, gesiht, gesihð, gesiehð, gesyhð; akin to D. gezicht, G. sicht, gesicht, Dan. sigte, Sw. sigt, from the root of E. see. See See, v. t.
F. signe, L. signum; cf. AS. segen, segn, a sign, standard, banner, also fr. L. signum.  Cf. Ensign, Resign, Seal a stamp, Signal, Signet.

OE. seinen to bless, originally, to make the sign of the cross over; in this sense fr. ASS. segnian (from segn, n.), or OF. seignier, F. signer, to mark, to sign (in sense 3), fr. L. signare to mark, set a mark upon, from signum. See Sign, n.
a.

OE. silver, selver, seolver, AS. seolfor, siolfur, siolufr, silofr, sylofr; akin to OS. silubar, OFries. selover, D. zilver, LG. sulver, OHG. silabar, silbar, G. silber, Icel. silfr, Sw. silfver, Dan. sölv, Goth. silubr, Russ. serebro, Lith. sidabras; of unknown origin.
a.

For sins, contr. fr. OE. sithens, sithenes, formed by an adverbial ending (cf. Besides) from OE. sithen, also shortened into sithe, sin, AS. siððan, syððan, seoððan, afterward, then, since, after; properly, after that; fr. sīð after, later, adv. and prep. (originally a comparative adv., akin to OS. sīð afterward, since, OHG. sīd, G. seit since, Goth. seiþus late, ni þanaseiþs no longer) + ðon instrumental of the demonstrative and article. See That.
AS. singan; akin to D. zingen, OS. & OHG. singan, G. singen, Icel. syngja, Sw. sjunga, Dan. synge, Goth. siggwan, and perhaps to E. say, v.t., or cf. Gr. &unr_;&unr_;&unr_; voice.  Cf. Singe, Song.
a.

OE. sister, fr. Icel. systir; also suster, from AS. sweostor, sweoster, swuster, akin to OFries. sweester, suster, LG. süster, suster, D. zuster, OS. & OHG. swestar, G. schwester, Icel. systir, Sw. syster, Dan. söster, Goth. swistar, Lith. ses&unr_;, Russ. sestra, Pol. siostra, L. soror, Skr. svasr. √298.  Cf. Cousin.

OE. sitten, AS.  sittan; akin to OS. sittian, OFries. sitta, D. zitten, G. sitzen, OHG. sizzen, Icel. sitja, SW. sitta, Dan. sidde, Goth. sitan, Russ. sidiete, L. sedere, Gr. 'e`zesqai, Skr. sad. √154.  Cf. Assess,Assize, Cathedral, Chair, Dissident, Excise, Insidious, Possess, Reside, Sanhedrim, Séance, Seat, n., Sedate, 4th Sell, Siege, Session, Set, v. t., Sizar, Size, Subsidy.
a.
See Sice, and Sise.

OIt. sisa glue used by painters, shortened fr. assisa, fr. assidere, p. p. assiso, to make to sit, to seat, to place, L. assidere to sit down; ad + sidere to sit down, akin to sedere to sit. See Sit, v. i., and cf. Assize, Size bulk.
Abbrev. from assize. See Assize, and cf. Size glue.

Icel. skil a distinction, discernment; akin to skilja to separate, divide, distinguish, Sw. skilja,. skille to separate, skiel reason, right, justice, Sw. skäl reason, Lith. skelli to cleave.  Cf. Shell, Shoal, a multitude.
Icel. skinn; akin to Sw. skinn, Dan. skind, AS. scinn, G. schined to skin.
OE. skie a cloud, Icel. sk&ymacr_;; akin to Sw. & Dan. sky; cf. AS. scūa, scūwa, shadow, Icel. skuggi; probably from the same root as E. scum. √158. See Scum, and cf. Hide skin, Obscure.

Cf. F. esclave, D. slaaf, Dan. slave, sclave, Sw. slaf, all fr. G. sklave, MHG. also slave, from the national name of the Slavonians, or Sclavonians (in LL. Slavi or Sclavi), who were frequently made slaves by the Germans. See Slav.

OE. slepen, AS. sl&unr_;pan; akin to OFries. sl&unr_;pa, OS. slāpan, D. slapen, OHG. slāfan, G. schlafen, Goth. sl&unr_;pan, and G. schlaff slack, loose, and L. labi to glide, slide, labare to totter.  Cf. Lapse.
AS. sl&aemacr_;p; akin to OFries. slēp, OS. slāp, D. slaap, OHG. slāf, G. schlaf, Goth. slēps. See Sleep, v. i.

OE. slippen; akin to LG. & D. slippen, MHG. slipfen (cf. Dan. slippe, Sw. slippa, Icel. sleppa), and fr. OE. slipen, AS. slīpan (in comp.), akin to G. schleifen to slide, glide, drag, whet, OHG. slīfan to slide, glide, make smooth, Icel. slīpa to whet; cf. also AS. sl&unr_;pan, Goth. sliupan, OS. slopian, OHG. sliofan, G. schliefen, schl&unr_;pfen, which seem to come from a somewhat different root form.  Cf. Slope, n.
AS. slipe, slip.

OE. smellen, smillen, smullen; cf. LG. smellen, smelen, smölen, schmelen, to smoke, to reek, D. smeulen to smolder, and E. smolder.  Cf. Smell, n.
OE. smel, smil, smul, smeol. See Smell, v. t.
OE. smilen; akin to Dan. smile, Sw. smila, MHG. smielen, smieren, L. mirari to wonder at, Skr. smi to smile; and probably to E. smicker. √173.  Cf. Admire, Marvel, Smirk.
CF. Dan. smiil, Sw. smil. See Smile, v. i.
LG. snaue, or D. snaauw, from LG. snau a snout, a beak.

OE. snow, snaw, AS. snāw; akin to D. sneeuw, OS. & OHG. snēo, G. schnee, Icel. snær, snjōr, snajār, Sw. snö, Dan. snee, Goth. snaiws, Lith. snëgas, Russ. snieg', Ir. & Gael. sneachd, W. nyf, L. nix, nivis, Gr. acc. ni`fa, also AS. snīwan to snow, G. schneien, OHG. snīwan, Lith. snigti, L. ningit it snows, Gr. ni`fei, Zend snizh to snow; cf. Skr. snih to be wet or sticky. √172.

OE. so, sa, swa, AS. swā; akin to OFries, sā, s&unr_;, D. zoo, OS. & OHG. s&unr_;, G. so, Icel. svā, sv&unr_;, svo, so, Sw. s&unr_;, Dan. saa, Goth. swa so, sw&unr_; as; cf. L. suus one's own, Skr. sva one's own, one's self. √192.  Cf. As, Custom, Ethic, Idiom, Such.
a.
OF. saoler, saouler, to satiate, F. soûler, L. satullare, fr. satullus, dim. of satur sated. See Satire.
OE. soile, F. sol, fr. L. solum bottom, soil; but the word has probably been influenced in form by soil a miry place.  Cf. Saloon, Soil a miry place, Sole of the foot.
OF. soil, souil, F. souille, from OF. soillier, F. souiller. See Soil to make dirty.
OE. soilen, OF. soillier, F. souiller, (assumed) LL. suculare, fr. L. sucula a little pig, dim. of sus a swine. See Sow, n.
See Soil to make dirty, Soil a miry place.

OE. souldier, soudiour, souder, OF. soldier, soldoier, soldeier, sodoier, soudoier, soudier, fr. L. solidus a piece of money (hence applied to the pay of a soldier), fr. solidus solid. See Solid, and cf. Sold, n.
OE. solucion, OF. solucion, F. solution, fr. L. solutio, fr. solvere, solutum, to loosen, dissolve. See Solve.
L. solvere, solutum; from a prefix so- expressing separation (cf. Sober) + luere to loosen; cf. OF. soldre, soudre. See Loose, and cf. Absolve.
a.

OE. sone, sune, AS. sunu; akin to D. zoon, OS., OFries., & OHG. sunu, G. sohn, Icel. sonr, Sw. son, Dan. sön, Goth. sunus, Lith. sunus, Russ. suin', Skr. sūnu (from sū to beget, to bear), and Gr. &unr_; son. √293.  Cf. Sow, n.
AS. song, sang, fr. singan to sing; akin to D. zang, G. sang, Icel. söngr, Goth. saggws. See Sing.
OE. sone, AS. sōna; cf. OFries. sōn, OS. sāna, sāno, OHG. sār, Goth. suns.
a.
AS. sund a swimming, akin to E. swim. See Swim.
a.
AS. sund a narrow sea or strait; akin to Icel., Sw., Dan. & G. sund, probably so named because it could be swum across. See Swim.
F. sonder; cf. AS. sundgyrd a sounding rod, sundline a sounding line (see Sound a narrow passage of water).
F. sonde. See Sound to fathom.
OE. soun, OF. son, sun, F. son, fr. L. sonus akin to Skr. svana sound, svan to sound, and perh. to E. swan.  Cf. Assonant, Consonant, Person, Sonata, Sonnet, Sonorous, Swan.
OE. sounen, sownen, OF. soner, suner, F. sonner, from L. sonare. See Sound a noise.

OE. south, suþ, AS. sūð for sunð; akin to D. zuid, OHG. sund, G. süd, süden, Icel. suðr, sunnr, Dan. syd, sönden, Sw. syd, söder, sunnan; all probably akin to E. sun, meaning, the side towards the sun. √297. See Sun.
a.
OE. space, F. espace, from L. spatium space; cf. Gr. spa^n to draw, to tear; perh. akin to E. span.  Cf. Expatiate.
Cf. OF. espacier, L. spatiari. See Space, n.
Cf. F. espacer. See Space, n.
OE. speken, AS. specan, sprecan; akin to OF.ries. spreka, D. spreken, OS. spreken, G. sprechen, OHG. sprehhan, and perhaps to Skr. sphūrj to crackle, to thunder.  Cf. Spark of fire, Speech.
a.
OE. speche, AS. sp&unr_;c, spr&unr_;, fr. specan, sprecan, to speak; akin to D. spraak speech, OHG. sprāhha, G. sprache, Sw. spr&unr_;k, Dan. sprog. See Speak.
AS. sp&unr_;d success, swiftness, from sp&unr_;wan to succeed; akin to D. spoedd, OHG. spuot success, spuot to succees, Skr. sphā to increase, grow fat. √170b.
AS. spēdan, fr. spēd, n.; akin to D. spoeden, G. sich sputen.  See Speed, n.

OE. speld, AS. speld a spill to light a candle with; akin to D. speld a pin, OD. spelle, G. spalten to split, OHG. spaltan, MHG. spelte a splinter, Icel. spjald a square tablet, Goth. spilda a writing tablet.  Cf. Spillsplinter, roll of paper, Spell to tell the letters of.
AS. spelian to supply another's place.
AS. spell a saying, tale, speech; akin to OS. & OHG. spel, Icel. spjall,Goth. spill.  Cf. Gospel, Spell to tell the letters of.

OE. spellen, spellien, tell, relate, AS. spellian, fr. spell a saying, tale; akin to MHG. spellen to relate, Goth. spill&unr_;n.e Spell a tale. In sense 4 and those following, OE. spellen, perhaps originally a different word, and from or influenced by spell a splinter, from the use of a piece of wood to point to the letters in schools: cf. D. spellen to spell.  Cf. Spell splinter.
AS. spendan (in comp.), fr. L. expendere or dispendere to weigh out, to expend, dispense. See Pendant, and cf. Dispend, Expend, Spence, Spencer.
OE. spoke, spake, AS. spāca; akin to D. speek, LG. speke, OHG. speihha, G. speiche. √170.  Cf. Spike a nail.
Cf. Scot. & D. spat, Dan. spette, Sw. spott spittle, slaver; from the root of E. spit. See Spit to eject from the mouth, and cf. Spatter.
a.
OE. spreden, AS. spraedan; akin to D. spreiden, spreijen, LG. spreden, spreen, spreien, G. spreiten, Dan. sprede, Sw. sprida.  Cf. Spray water flying in drops.
AS. spring a fountain, a leap. See Spring, v. i.

OF. esquarre, esquierre, F. équerre a carpenter's square (cf. It. squadra), fr. (assumed) LL. exquadrare to make square; L. ex + quadrus a square, fr. quattuor four. See Four, and cf. Quadrant, Squad, Squire a square.
a.
Cf. OF. escarrer, esquarrer. See Square, n.

OE. standen; AS. standan; akin to OFries. stonda, stān, D. staan, OS. standan, stān, OHG. stantan, stān, G. stehen, Icel. standa, Dan. staae, Sw. stå, Goth. standan, Russ. stoiate, L. stare, Gr. 'ista`nai to cause to stand, sth^nai to stand, Skr. sthā.  √163.  Cf. Assist, Constant, Contrast, Desist, Destine, Ecstasy, Exist, Interstice, Obstacle, Obstinate, Prest, n., Rest remainder, Solstice, Stable, a. & n., Staff, Stage, Stall, n., Stamen, Stanchion, Stanza, State, n., Statute, Stead, Steed, Stool, Stud of horses, Substance, System.
AS. stand. See Stand, v. i.

OE. sterre, AS. steorra; akin to OFries. stera, OS. sterro, D. ster, OHG. sterno, sterro, G. stern, Icel. stjarna, Sw. stjerna, Dan. stierne, Goth. staírnō, Armor. & Corn. steren, L. stella, Gr. 'asth`r, 'a`stron, Skr. star; perhaps from a root meaning, to scatter, Skr. st&rsdot_;, L. sternere (cf. Stratum), and originally applied to the stars as being strewn over the sky, or as being scatterers or spreaders of light. √296.  Cf. Aster, Asteroid, Constellation, Disaster, Stellar.

OE. sterten; akin to D. storten to hurl, rush, fall, G. stürzen, OHG. sturzen to turn over, to fall, Sw. störta to cast down, to fall, Dan. styrte, and probably also to E. start a tail; the original sense being, perhaps, to show the tail, to tumble over suddenly.  √166.  Cf. Start a tail.
Perh. from D. storten, which has this meaning also.
OE. stert a tail, AS. steort; akin to LG. stert, steert, D. staart, G. sterz, Icel. stertr, Dan. stiert, Sw. stjert. √166.  Cf. Stark naked, under Stark, Start, v. i.
From Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
OE. stat, OF. estat, F. état, fr. L. status a standing, position, fr. stare, statum, to stand. See Stand, and cf. Estate, Status.
a.
F., fr. L. statio, from stare, statum, to stand. See Stand.
AS. staeg, akin to D., G., Icel., Sw., & Dan. stag; cf. OF. estai, F. étai, of Teutonic origin.
OF. estayer, F. étayer to prop, fr. OF. estai, F. étai, a prop, probably fr. OD. stade, staeye, a prop, akin to E. stead; or cf. stay a rope to support a mast.  Cf. Staid, a., Stay, v. i.
√163. See Stay to hold up, prop.
Cf. OF. estai, F. étai support, and E. stay a rope to support a mast.

OE. stede place, AS. stede; akin to LG. & D. stede, OS. stad, stedi, OHG. stat, G. statt, stätte, Icel. staðr, Dan. sted, Sw. stad, Goth. staþs, and E. stand.  √163. See Stand, and cf. Staith, Stithy.

OE. stem, steem, vapor, flame, AS. steám vapor, smoke, odor; akin to D. stoom steam, perhaps originally, a pillar, or something rising like a pillar; cf. Gr. sty`ein to erect, sty^los a pillar, and E. stand.
AS. stēl, st&ymacr_;l, st&ymacr_;le; akin to D. staal, G. stahl, OHG. stahal, Icel. stāl, Dan. staal, Sw. stål, Old Prussian stakla.
AS. st&ymacr_;lan: cf. Icel. staela. See Steel, n.

AS. staeppan; akin to OFries. steppa, D. stappen to step, stap a step, OHG. stepfen to step, G. stapfe a footstep, OHG. stapfo, G. stufe a step to step on; cf. Gr. &unr_; to shake about, handle roughly, stamp (?).  Cf. Stamp, n. & a.
AS. staepe. See Step, v. i.
OE. sticke, AS. sticca; akin to stician to stab, prick, pierce, G. stecken a stick, staff, OHG. steccho, Icel. stik a stick. See Stick, v. t..

OE. stikien, v.t. & i., combined with steken, whence E. stuck), AS. stician, v.t. & i., and (assumed) stecan, v.t.; akin to OFries. steka, OS. stekan, OHG. stehhan, G. stechen, and to Gr. &unr_; to prick, Skr. tij to be sharp.  Cf. Distinguish, Etiquette, Extinct, Instigate, Instinct, Prestige, Stake, Steak, Stick, n., Stigma, Stimulate, Sting, Stitch in sewing, Style for or in writing.
a.
Cf. G. stille.
AS. stille quietly. See Still, a. The modern senses come from the idea of stopping and staying still, or motionless.
AS. stillan, from stille still, quiet, firm. See Still, a.
Cf. OE. stillatorie. See Still, v., to distill.
Abbreviated fr. distill.
L. stillare.  Cf. Distill.
OE. ston, stan, AS. stān; akin to OS. & OFries. stēn, D. steen, G. stein, Icel. steinn, Sw. sten, Dan. steen, Goth. stains, Russ. stiena a wall, Gr. &unr_;, &unr_;, a pebble. √167.  Cf. Steen.
From Stone, n.: cf. AS. st&unr_;nan, Goth. stainjan.

OE. stoppen, AS. stoppian (in comp.); akin to LG. & D. stoppen, G. stopfen, Icel. stoppa, Sw. stoppa, Dan. stoppe; all probably fr. LL. stopare, stupare, fr. L. stuppa the coarse part of flax, tow, oakum.  Cf. Estop, Stuff, Stupe a fomentation.
OE. stor, stoor, OF. estor, provisions, supplies, fr. estorer to store. See Store, v. t.
a.
OE. storen, OF. estorer to construct, restore, store, LL. staurare, for L. instaurare to renew, restore; in + staurare (in comp.) Cf. Instore, Instaurate, Restore, Story a floor.
OF. estoré, estorée, built, erected, p. p. of estorer to build, restore, to store. See Store, v. t.
OE. storie, OF. estoire, F. histoire, fr. L. historia. See History.
a.
a.

AS. streám; akin to OFries. strām, OS. strōm, D. stroom, G. strom, OHG. stroum, strūm, Dan. & Sw. ström, Icel. straumr, Ir. sroth, Lith. srove, Russ. struia, Gr. "ry`sis a flowing, "rei^n to flow, Skr. sru. √174.  Cf. Catarrh, Diarrhea, Rheum, Rhythm.
OE. strete, AS. str&aemacr_;t, fr. L. strata (sc. via) a paved way, properly fem. p. p. of sternere, stratum, to spread; akin to E. strew. See Strew, and cf. Stratum, Stray, v. & a.

OE. strecchen, AS. streccan; akin to D. strekken, G. strecken, OHG. strecchen, Sw. sträcka, Dan. straekke; cf. AS. straeck, strec, strong, violent, G. strack straight; of uncertain origin, perhaps akin to E. strong.  Cf. Straight.

OE. string, streng, AS. streng; akin to D. streng, G. strang, Icel. strengr, Sw. sträng, Dan. straeng; probably from the adj., E. strong (see Strong); or perhaps originally meaning, twisted, and akin to E. strangle.
a.
L. studens, -entis, p. pr. of studere to study. See Study, n.
OE. studie, L. studium, akin to studere to study; possibly akin to Gr. &unr_; haste, zeal, &unr_; to hasten; cf. OF. estudie, estude, F. étude.  Cf. Etude, Student, Studio, Study, v. i.
OE. studien, OF. estudier, F. étudier. See Study, n.
a.
From L. subjectus, through an old form of F. sujet. See Subject, a.
F., fr. L. substantia, fr. substare to be under or present, to stand firm; sub under + stare to stand. See Stand.
L. subtractus, p. p. of subtrahere to draw from beneath, withdraw, remove; sub under + trahere to draw. See Trace, v. t., and cf. Substract.
L. successus: cf. F. succès. See Succeed.

OE. sugre, F. sucre (cf. It. zucchero, Sp. azúcar), fr. Ar. sukkar, assukkar, fr. Skr. çarkarā sugar, gravel; cf. Per. shakar.  Cf. Saccharine, Sucrose.
L. suggestus, p. p. of suggerere to put under, furnish, suggest; sub under + gerere to carry, to bring. See Jest.
OE. suite, F. suite, OF. suite, sieute, fr. suivre to follow, OF. sivre; perhaps influenced by L. secta. See Sue to follow, and cf. Sect, Suite.
From Sum, v.
F. sommier a rafter, the same word as sommier a beast of burden. See Sumpter.
OE. sumer, somer, AS. sumor, sumer; akin to OFries. sumur, D. zomer, OS. sumar, G. sommer, OHG. & Icel. sumar, Dan. sommer, Sw. sommar, W. haf, Zend hama, Skr. samā year. √292.
OE. sunne, sonne, AS. sunne; akin to OFries. sunne, D. zon, OS. & OHG. sunna, G. sonne, Icel. sunna, Goth. sunna; perh. fr. same root as L. sol. √297.  Cf. Solar, South.
For older supploy, F. suppléer, OF. also supployer, (assumed) LL. suppletare, from L. supplere, suppletum; sub under + plere to fill, akin to plenus full. See Plenty.
a.
F. supporter, L. supportare to carry on, to convey, in LL., to support, sustain; sub under + portare to carry. See Port demeanor.

a.
F. See Sur-, and Face, and cf. Superficial.
F. surprise, fr. surprendre, surpris; sur over + prendre to take, L. prehendere. See Sur-, and Prehensile.
From Surprise, n.: cf. F. surprendre, p. p. surpris.
AS. swimman; akin to D. zwemmen, OHG. swimman, G. schwimmen, Icel. svimma, Dan. swömme, Sw. simma.  Cf. Sound an air bladder, a strait.

OE. swime dizziness, vertigo, AS. swīma; akin to D. zwijm, Icel. svimi dizziness, svina to subside, svīa to abate, G. schwindel dizziness, schwinden to disappear, to dwindle, OHG. swīnan to dwindle.  Cf. Squemish, Swindler.

OE. sillable, OF. sillabe, F. syllabe, L. syllaba, Gr. &unr_; that which is held together, several letters taken together so as to form one sound, a syllable, fr. &unr_; to take together; &unr_; with + &unr_; to take; cf. Skr. labh, rabh.  Cf. Lemma, Dilemma.

L. systema, Gr. &unr_;, fr. &unr_; to place together; sy`n with + &unr_; to place: cf. F. système. See Stand.

OE. talien to speak (see tale, v. i. & n.).

OE. test test, or cupel, potsherd, F. têt, from L. testum an earthen vessel; akin to testa a piece of burned clay, an earthen pot, a potsherd, perhaps for tersta, and akin to torrere to patch, terra earth (cf. Thirst, and Terrace), but cf. Zend tasta cup.  Cf. Test a shell, Testaceous, Tester a covering, a coin, Testy, Tête-à-tête.
L. testis.  Cf. Testament, Testify.
L. testari. See Testament.

OE. than, thon, then, thanne, thonne, thenne, than, then, AS. ðanne, ðonne, ðaenne; akin to D. dan, OHG. danne, G. dann then, denn than, for, Goth. þan then, and to E. the, there, that. See That, and cf. Then.

AS. þanc, þonc, thanks, favor, thought; akin to OS. thank favor, pleasure, thanks, D. & G. dank thanks, Icel. þökk, Dan. tak, Sw. tack, Goth. þagks thanks; -- originally, a thought, a thinking. See Think.
AS. þancian. See Thank, n.

AS. ðaet, neuter nom. & acc. sing. of the article (originally a demonstrative pronoun). The nom. masc. sē, and the nom. fem. seó are from a different root. AS. ðaet is akin to D. dat, G. das, OHG. daz, Sw. & Dan. det, Icel. þat (masc. sā, fem. sō), Goth. þata (masc. sa, fem. sō), Gr. &unr_; (masc. &unr_;, fem. &unr_;), Skr. tat (for tad, masc. sas, fem. sā); cf. L. istud that. √184.  Cf. The, Their, They, Them, This, Than, Since.

OE. thair, fr. Icel. þeirra, þeira, of them, but properly gen. pl. of the definite article; akin to AS. ðāra, ð&aemacr_;ra, gen. pl. of the definite article, or fr. AS. ð&aemacr_;ra, influenced by the Scandinavian use. See That.

AS. þing a thing, cause, assembly, judicial assembly; akin to þingan to negotiate, þingian to reconcile, conciliate, D. ding a thing, OS. thing thing, assembly, judicial assembly, G. ding a thing, formerly also, an assembly, court, Icel. þing a thing, assembly, court, Sw. & Dan. ting; perhaps originally used of the transaction of or before a popular assembly, or the time appointed for such an assembly; cf. G. dingen to bargain, hire, MHG. dingen to hold court, speak before a court, negotiate, Goth. þeihs time, perhaps akin to L. tempus time.  Cf. Hustings, and Temporal of time.

OE. thinken, properly, to seem, from AS. þyncean (cf. Methinks), but confounded with OE. thenken to think, fr. AS. þencean (imp. þōhte); akin to D. denken, dunken, OS. thenkian, thunkian, G. denken, dünken, Icel. þekkja to perceive, to know, þykkja to seem, Goth. þagkjan, þaggkjan, to think, þygkjan to think, to seem, OL. tongere to know.  Cf. Thank, Thought.
a.

OE. this, thes, AS. ðēs, masc., ðeós, fem., ðis, neut.; akin to OS. these, D. deze, G. dieser, OHG. diser, deser, Icel. þessi; originally from the definite article + a particle -se, -si; cf. Goth. sai behold. See The, That, and cf. These, Those.
OE. þos, þas, AS. ðās, nom. and acc. pl. of ðēs this. See This, and cf. These.

OE. thogh, þah, AS. ðeáh, ð&aemacr_;h, ðēh; akin to OS. thōh, OFries. thach, D. & G. doch but, yet, OHG. doh but, yet though, Icel. þō yet, nevertheless, Sw. dock, Dan. dog, Goth. þáuh, þáu, than, or, yet; of uncertain origin.  √184.
OE. þoght, þouht, AS. þōht, geþōht, fr. þencean to think; akin to D. gedachte thought, MHG. dāht, gedāht, Icel. þōttr, þōtti. See Think.

OE. þousend, þusend, AS. þūsend; akin to OS. thūsundig, thūsind, OFries. thusend, D. duizend, G. tausend, OHG. tūsunt, dūsunt, Icel. þūsund, þūshund, Sw. tusen, Dan. tusind, Goth. þūsundi, Lith. tukstantis, Russ. tuisiacha; of uncertain origin.

OE. thus, AS. ðus; akin to OFries. & OS. thus, D. dus, and E. that; cf. OHG. sus. See That.

OE. ti&unr_;en, teyen, AS. tīgan, tiégan, fr. teág, teáh, a rope; akin to Icel. taug, and AS. teón to draw, to pull. See Tug, v. t., and cf. Tow to drag.

Cf. Tool, v. t., 2.
CF. OD. dop, top, OHG., MNG., & dial. G. topf; perhaps akin to G. topf a pot.

L. tubus; akin to tuba a trumpet: cf F. tube.

OF. value, fr. valoir, p. p. valu, to be worth, fr. L. valere to be strong, to be worth. See Valiant.
